## Theorem: mathd_numbertheory_451

Theorem: mathd_numbertheory_451
Given: S : finset ℕ
Given: h₀ : ∀ (n : ℕ), n ∈ S ↔ 2010 ≤ n ∧ n ≤ 2019 ∧ ∃ m, ((nat.divisors m).card = 4 ∧ ∑ p in (nat.divisors m), p = n)
Prove: ∑ k in S, k = 2016

Goal: ∑ k in S, k = 2016

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "A natural number with exactly four divisors is either p^3 or pq for distinct primes p,q; checking the possible sums of divisors shows that among 2010 through 2019, only 2016 occurs, so S = {2016}.",
  "plan": [
    "Characterize all numbers with exactly four divisors.",
    "Use the divisor-sum formula to determine which such numbers can have sum 2010 through 2019.",
    "Show that 2016 is attainable and that every other candidate is impossible.",
    "Conclude that S contains exactly 2016, so its sum is 2016."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "If a natural number m has exactly four divisors, then m is either of the form p^3 for a prime p or of the form p*q for distinct primes p and q.",
      "reasoning": "A number has exactly four positive divisors precisely when its prime factorization has either one prime with exponent 3, giving divisors 1,p,p^2,p^3, or two distinct primes each with exponent 1, giving divisors 1,p,q,pq.",
      "facts_used": [
        "classification of integers with four divisors"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "If m = p^3 for a prime p, then the sum of the divisors of m is 1 + p + p^2 + p^3.",
      "reasoning": "The divisors of p^3 are exactly 1, p, p^2, and p^3, so the divisor sum is their sum.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "If m = p*q for distinct primes p and q, then the sum of the divisors of m is 1 + p + q + pq = (p+1)(q+1).",
      "reasoning": "The divisors of pq are exactly 1, p, q, and pq, so the sum is the sum of these four terms; the factorization is a simple algebraic rewrite.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "No number of the form 1 + p + p^2 + p^3 lies in the interval [2010,2019].",
      "reasoning": "Testing the possible primes shows p = 11 gives 1+11+121+1331 = 1464, while p = 13 gives 1+13+169+2197 = 2380; since the expression is strictly increasing in p, it cannot fall between 2010 and 2019.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 2",
        "monotonicity of polynomials on प्राकृतिक numbers"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Among numbers of the form (p+1)(q+1) with distinct primes p,q, the only value in [2010,2019] is 2016.",
      "reasoning": "Since 2010 through 2019 are all even except 2011, 2013, 2015, 2017, 2019, the factors p+1 and q+1 must be at least 2 and at least one is even. Checking factor pairs of 2016 in the range compatible with primes gives 2016 = 48·42 = (47+1)(41+1), corresponding to distinct primes 47 and 41. For the other integers 2010, 2011, ..., 2019, no factorization into two numbers each one more than a prime matches the required parity and primality constraints.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 3",
        "finite checking of small integers",
        "properties of prime numbers"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "2016 satisfies the defining property of membership in S.",
      "reasoning": "Take m = 47·41. Then m has exactly four divisors, namely 1, 41, 47, and 47·41, and their sum is 1+41+47+47·41 = 2016. Also 2010 ≤ 2016 ≤ 2019, so the condition in h₀ holds for n = 2016.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 3",
        "direct verification"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "For every n ∈ S, we have n = 2016.",
      "reasoning": "By h₀, any n in S must lie between 2010 and 2019 and must be the sum of divisors of some m with exactly four divisors. Steps 4 and 5 show that the only such n in this interval is 2016, so every element of S equals 2016.",
      "facts_used": [
        "h₀",
        "step 4",
        "step 5"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "S = {2016}.",
      "reasoning": "Step 6 shows every element of S is 2016, and step 5 shows 2016 is in S.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 6",
        "step 5"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "∑ k in S, k = 2016.",
      "reasoning": "A finset consisting of the single element 2016 has sum 2016.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 7",
        "sum over singleton finset"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "2016"
}

